text: From: Sentry Newsletter <learn@sentry.io>Date: Fri, Mar 1, 2024 at 5:14 AMSubject: [February] Launch Week is back, Syntax highlighting, new Kotlin SDK and more...To: <om.avhad@fischerjordan.com>Welcome to February's Misprint Mnothly.Sentry Launch Week is back! Mark your calendar and get ready for new products, exclusive demos, and thrilling talks about Metrics, Performance Monitoring, AI, Code Coverage, and Debugging. It’s all happening on YouTube, so all you need to do is sit back and watch the releases roll out. Join us live March 18-22, 2024, 9 am PT Product Updates Sentry is (probably) better this month. Open pull request comments for GitHubSee unhandled issues related to your code changes on open pull requests in GitHub. By flagging potential issues while your context is fresh, you can triage and prioritize relevant issues faster. Learn more.Issue replay clipsReplays are now embedded directly within the issue details page so you can quickly assess the reproduction steps and debug the issue without context switching. Learn more.Canvas support for Session ReplayTo give you the context needed to debug tricky errors, you can now configure Session Replay to show HTML canvas elements in the replay. Learn more.Syntax highlightingThe readability of your code in Sentry just got a big upgrade. Stack traces now incorporate syntax highlighting for all major languages. Learn more.Removing archived issues from metric alertsYou can now create or edit existing Sentry alerts to exclude error events associated with archived issues. Reduce alerts for archived or resolved issues by filtering error events by is:unresolved in your alert settings. Learn more.Kotlin Multiplatform SDK v0.4.0 is now available – it supports the official stable release of Kotlin Multiplatform (v1.9.20). Check out our revamped docs for a smooth onboarding experience.Rage click issues – EA releaseRage clicks are now an issue type so you can get alerted when your users are frustrated by unresponsive elements on your page and triage the problem - now available for early adopters. Learn More. Use case of the month: Yuki Read how Yuki, an accounting software company based in the Netherlands, use Queries to identify their top regressed queries and associated API endpoints so they can prioritize and triage performance issues faster – reducing engineer (and customer) frustration – and decreasing time to resolution by 24x. Syntax podcast of month: Own your own PaaS Host your own apps for cheaper AND keep control with self-hosted Kubernetes and PaaS options.Scott and Wes discuss about the benefits of owning your own PaaS (platform as a service), the main alternatives in the space, and ways to make passion projects more financially viable! Community Updates What's going on with us, you, and the open-source community. Upcoming EventsMarch 6: [Workshop] Mobile app performance monitoring best practices (Virtual)March 13: SF Python x Sentry Meetup (San Francisco, CA)March 18-20: SRECon Americas (San Francisco, CA)March 18-22: Sentry Launch Week (Virtual)March 20-22: KubeCon EU (Paris, France)March 20-22: Game Developers Conference (San Francisco, CA)RecentIntro to Sentry - Live Product TourIdentify, trace, and fix endpoint regression issuesMobile crash reporting and debugging best practicesDebugging your Next.js projectContributed BlogsHow to deal with API rate limits.Net improvementsNavigating cookies at Sentry: A legal perspectiveWant to see what else you missed? Check out the Sentry blog and YouTube channel for new content and product updates. By the way, we're hiring for a lot of roles.45 Fremont Street, 8th Floor, San Francisco, CA 94105This email was sent to om.avhad@fischerjordan.com. If you no longer wish to receive these emails you may unsubscribe at any time.
